# JavaScript Coding Conventions

## ES6 Modules

- Always use ES6 import/export syntax
- Include `.js` extension in all imports (required for Thunderbird)
- Use default exports for classes
- Use named exports for utilities and constants

```javascript
// Good
import Author from "./Author.js";
import { Scope } from "./Provider.js";

// Bad - missing .js extension
import Author from "./Author";
```

## Class Structure

### Constructor Documentation

Always document constructor parameters with JSDoc:

```javascript
/**
 * Creates an instance of ClassName.
 * @param {string} name - The name parameter
 * @param {Object} options - Configuration options
 */
constructor(name, options = {}) {
  this.name = name;
}
```

### Method Documentation

Document all public methods with:

- Description of what the method does
- `@param` for each parameter with type and description
- `@returns` with type and description
- `@throws` if the method can throw errors

```javascript
/**
 * Gets the profile picture URL for the given author.
 * @param {Author} author - The author to get the URL for.
 * @returns {Promise<string>} The profile picture URL.
 * @throws {Error} If the author is invalid.
 */
async getUrl(author) {
  // implementation
}
```

## Async/Await Pattern

- Prefer `async/await` over Promise chains
- Use `try/catch` for error handling in async functions
- Always handle promise rejections

```javascript
// Good
async function fetchAvatar(author) {
  try {
    const url = await provider.getUrl(author);
    return url;
  } catch (error) {
    console.error("Error fetching avatar:", error);
    return null;
  }
}
```

## Naming Conventions

### Variables and Functions

- Use camelCase for variables and functions
- Use descriptive names that indicate purpose
- Boolean variables should start with `is`, `has`, `should`, etc.

```javascript
let avatarUrl;
let isContactsEnabled;
async function fetchProfilePicture() {}
```

### Classes

- Use PascalCase for class names
- Service classes should end with "Service"
- Strategy classes should end with "Strategy"
- Provider classes should end with provider name (e.g., "Gravatar")

```javascript
class AvatarService {}
class CacheStrategy {}
class GravatarProvider {}
```

### Constants

- Use UPPER_SNAKE_CASE for constants
- Group related constants in objects or exported constants

```javascript
const MAX_REQUEST_SIZE = 50;

const Status = {
  WAITING: "[WAITING]",
  READY: "[READY]",
};
```

## Error Handling

### Console Logging

- Use `console.log()` for debugging (remove before production)
- Use `console.warn()` for non-critical issues
- Use `console.error()` for errors with context information

```javascript
console.error("Error fetching avatar for", author.getAuthor(), ":", error);
```

### Graceful Degradation

Always provide fallbacks:

```javascript
try {
  const version = Services.appinfo.version;
  return parseInt(version.split(".")[0], 10);
} catch (error) {
  console.error("Error getting version:", error);
  // Default to safe fallback
  return 145;
}
```

## Version-Aware Code

When implementing features that depend on Thunderbird version:

```javascript
const tbVersion = getThunderbirdVersion();
const useCanvas = tbVersion >= 145;

if (useCanvas) {
  // TB 145+ implementation
} else {
  // TB < 145 implementation
}
```

## String Handling

- Use template literals for string interpolation
- Use `.toLowerCase()` for case-insensitive comparisons
- Store lowercase versions when using as keys

```javascript
// Good
const key = author.getAuthor().toLowerCase();
console.log(`Processing avatar for ${author.getAuthor()}`);

// Avoid
const key = author.getAuthor(); // May cause cache misses
console.log("Processing avatar for " + author.getAuthor());
```

## Array and Object Operations

- Use modern array methods (map, filter, reduce, etc.)
- Use object destructuring when appropriate
- Use `for...of` for simple iterations, `for...in` for object keys

```javascript
// Array iteration
for (const item of items) {
  process(item);
}

// Object iteration
for (const key in this.cache) {
  if (this.cache[key] === Status.WAITING) {
    waiting++;
  }
}
```

## Browser API Usage

- Always handle browser API errors with try/catch
- Use `await` for browser API calls that return promises
- Check for API availability when using optional features

```javascript
try {
  const data = await browser.storage.local.get(key);
  return data[key];
} catch (error) {
  console.error("Storage error:", error);
  return null;
}
```

## Performance Considerations

- Cache results when possible (use session cache or persistent storage)
- Implement rate limiting for network requests
- Use polling with reasonable delays (200ms) when waiting for async operations

```javascript
// Rate limiting check
if (this.countWaitingAvatars() > MAX_REQUEST_SIZE) {
  console.warn("Too many requests in progress");
  return null;
}
```
